Guangdong Key Laboratory of Integrated Agro-environmental Pollution Control and Management, Institute of Eco-environmental and Soil Sciences, Guangdong Academy of Sciences Guangzhou 510650 China In this study, a novel and highly efficient ORR catalyst is designed via the pyrolysis of zeolitic imidazole framework-8 (ZIF-8) under the protection of hypercrosslinked iron porphyrins. Fe3O4 nanoparticles with oxygen vacancies are formed in situ and promoting catalytic efficiency. Benefiting from the synergistic effect among the Fe3O4 and ZIF-8 skeleton, the hybrid catalyst exhibits excellent ORR activity even surpassing commercial Pt/C. The pyrolyzation temperature is studied in detail and determined to be a crucial parameter for ORR performance. Nano-Fe3O4, which has high catalytic efficiency, is formed in situ at 800 ℃. Amorphous iron is formed at 600 ℃ and 700 ℃, and zero-valent iron is formed at 900 ℃. The content of oxygen vacancies, Fe–N, and graphite–N, which are beneficial to the ORR reaction, are all reached to a maximum at 800 ℃. This study provides a new approach to design highly active Fe3O4-based electrocatalytic materials. Graphical Abstract ga1 Keywords Fe3O4 nanoparticles Hypercrosslined iron porphyrins ZIF-8 Oxygen vacancies Oxygen reduction reaction 1 Introduction Owing to the global population explosion, a growing energy demand, and economic expansion driven by fossil fuels, the environment is facing serious threats [1–3]. To produce cleaner energy for reducing environmental risks, fuel cells and metal–air batteries were invented, which have the advantages of a high energy density, high conversion efficiency, and low emissions [4,5]. In a fuel cell or metal–air battery, the oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) at the cathode is a key process that determines the electrochemical conversion efficiency; thus, the performance of the cathode reaction catalyst is crucial for the overall performance of the device [6]. Therefore, the development of an economical, high-efficiency, and high-stability cathode catalysts for ORR is crucial for the widespread application of this new energy conversion technology [7–9]. Pt-based catalysts have the highest catalytic efficiency for ORR, but noble metals are expensive. Researchers have attempted to use nonprecious metals instead of platinum [10,11], but the catalytic performance of other transition metals usually lags far behind commercial Pt/C. In recent years, high-efficiency ORR catalysts with a Fe–Nx/C structure were reported [12]. Active sites in Fe-based nitrogen-doped carbon materials, including FeNx [13], FexC [14], and metal oxides [15], have been identified, which makes them one of the most promising nonprecious metal catalysts that can replace Pt [16–19]. Therefore, method to design efficient Fe–Nx/C catalysts and clarify the corresponding synthesis and catalytic mechanism has become an important issue in this field. Zeolitic imidazolate frameworks (ZIFs) are high-catalytic-performance metal organic framework structures discovered in recent years [20]. ZIFs have zeolite-like three-dimensional topological structures and abundant carbon and nitrogen ligands. They also have high carbon content and large surface area, which is expected to synthesize porous carbon directly upon carbonization. In particular, the nitrogen containing methylimidazole ligand in ZIFs is expected to have contribution to the formation of nitrogen-doped porous carbon during carbonization [21,22]. Thus, ZIFs are good candidates as carbon precursor templates to design porous, nonprecious metal–carbon hybrid materials [23] and they have been wildly used in the field of electrocatalytic catalyst [24], functionally tailored materials [25], and rechargeable batteries[26]. Metal Fe is generally regarded as the active site of ORR. The ORR catalytic performance of ZIFs was reported can be improved by compounding with Fe-containing structures such as porphyrin and phthalocyanine [27,28]. The Fe−N and C−N structure on the surface provided highly active reactive site, meanwhile, the coordination of electron-donating ligands to active Fe-porphyrins dramatically accelerates the rates of ORR at molecular level via changing the electronic properties [28]. In addition, although iron oxides probably have low electrocatalytic activity owing to their poor conductivity, the carbon skeleton enhances its conductivity, thereby reducing this disadvantage. Moreover, constructing oxygen vacancies in iron oxides can further improve the ORR performance [2]. For example, Deng et al. coupling hollow Fe3O4 nanoparticles with oxygen vacancy on mesoporous carbon, a half-wave potential of 30 mV more positive than that of commercial Pt/C was obtained in ORR [29]. Although coupling Fe3O4 in a ZIF could improve the ORR performance, the structure of carbon precursor and iron oxides are usually instability at high temperature and electrolyte. Hence, designing high stability Fe3O4-based material and creating oxygen vacancies in the structure is a promising idea for obtaining high-performance ORR catalysts. Using hypercrosslinked iron porphyrin instead of iron porphyrin to coat ZIF-8 can probably improve the skeleton stability. Therefore, in this study, an ORR catalyst was synthesized by selecting zeolitic imidazole framework-8 (ZIF-8, 2-methylimidazole zinc salt) and tetraphenylporphyrin iron (TPPFe) as the crosslinking reaction precursors and pyrolyzing at high temperatures (600 ℃, 700 ℃, 800 ℃, and 900 ℃) under argon protection. Oxygen-containing functional groups cooperate on the surface of ZIF-8 by protonation were expected to oxidize the doped iron on tetraphenylporphyrin skeleton [30,31]. Introducing hypercrosslinked polymers (HCPs) were expected to coat ZIF and reduce the damage to the skeleton during the carbonization process. Because oxygen vacancies are usually generated by annealing in a reductive atmosphere and the crystal form of iron oxides is closely associated with temperature, different carbonization temperatures were used in this study for discussing the relationship between ORR efficiency, iron species, and oxygen vacancies. The purpose of this study is to design a high-performance and stability Fe3O4-based ORR electrocatalyst by coupling with hyper crosslinked carbon skeleton and to clarify the influence of iron species and oxygen vacancies on catalytic performance. 2 Materials and methods 2.1 Materials Benzaldehyde, pyrrole, propionic acid, biphenyl, Zn(NO3)2.6H2O, 2-methylimidazole, formaldehyde dimethyl acetal, methyl alcohol, and 1,2-dichloroethane were procured from Aladdin Chemical Reagent Co. Ltd. (USA); iron (III) chloride from Sinopharm Chemical Reagent Co. Ltd. (China); and Nafion solution (5 %) from Dupont China Holding Co. Ltd (USA). 2.2 Synthesis of ZIF-8 The ZIF-8 was synthesized based on the methods reported in previous studies [32,33]. Consequently, for this purpose, Zn (NO3)2.6 H2O (20 mmol) and 2-methylimidazole (75 mmol) were dissolved in 150 mL of methanol. The 2-methylimidazole solution was poured into the Zn (NO3)2.6H2O solution before mixing and stirring at 25 ℃ for 24 h; then, the resulting white precipitate was centrifuged several times, washed with methanol, and dried at 60 ℃. 2.3 Synthesis of FeTPP–ZIF-8 TPPFe-based polymer was synthesized according to methods used in a previous work[34]. According to a typical procedure, TPPFe (0.24 mmol), biphenyl (0.96 mmol), and ZIF-8 (96 mg) were dissolved in 1,2-dichloroethane (DCE, 5 mL). After complete dissolution of the substrate, dimethoxymethane (0.48 mmol) and anhydrous FeCl3 (12 mmol) were added at room temperature. The resulting mixture was heated at 45 ℃ for 5 h and 80 ℃ for 19 h to complete the condensation reaction and obtain a porous structure. Due to the low boiling point of the solvent and crosslinker, 45 ℃ was used in the initial stage. However, increasing temperature can increase the crosslinking degree of the reaction and enhance the rigidity of the polymer materials. Hence, 80 ℃ was used in the following 19 h. Subsequently, the product was extracted by a Soxhlet extractor in methanol until the filtrate liquor was colorless and dried in a vacuum oven at 60 ℃ for 12 h. The sample was labeled as FeTPP–ZIF-8. The other carbon precursor synthesis methods were similar, and the specific proportion of raw materials is shown in Table S1. 2.4 Synthesis of FeTPP–ZIF-800 FeTPP–ZIF-8 was carbonized under an atmosphere of Ar at 2 ℃ min−1 from room temperature to 800 ℃ and held for 2 h. Finally, the catalyst was naturally cooled to room temperature and labeled as FeTPP–ZIF-800. Other catalysts were treated similarly and labeled as FeTPP–ZIF-600, FeTPP–ZIF-700, FeTPP–ZIF-900, FeTPP0.47–ZIF-800, FeTPP0.31–ZIF-800, FeTPP-800, and ZIF-800 with the general form being FeTPPiron ratio–ZIF-temperature. TPP–ZIF-800 was synthesized using TPP instead of FeTPP in the synthetic steps of FeTPP–ZIF-800. 2.5 Synthesis of FeTPP–ZIF-800-HCl FeTPP–ZIF-800 was treated with 0.5 M of HCl, heated in a water bath at 50 ℃ and stirred for 24 h. It was washed with deionized water via centrifugation several times and dried in vacuum to obtain FeTPP–ZIF-800–HCl. 2.6 Characterizations The morphology and structure of all materials were characterized by scanning electron microscopy (SEM, Zeiss 500), transmission electron microscopy (TEM, FEI Talos F200s), and high-angle annular dark-field scanning transmission electron microscopy (HAADF-STEM, Titan G2 FEI). N2 adsorption and desorption measurements were performed on a Autosorb iQ MP analyzer at 77 K, and specific surface areas (SBET) were calculated using the Brunauer–Emmett–Teller (BET) method. X-ray diffraction (XRD, BRUCKER D8) measurements were performed in the range from 5° to 80° using Cu Kα radiation. Raman spectroscopy (Renishwa, inVia Reflex) was performed with an excitation wavelength of 532 nm. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS, ESCALAB 250 Xi, Thermo Fisher) was performed using an Al Kα X-ray source. Inductively coupled plasma atomic emission spectrometry (ICP-OES, Optima 8000 system, PerkinElmer) was performed. 2.7 Electrochemical measurements As for the preparation of the working electrode, 5 mg of the catalyst was added to a 0.1 wt% Nafion solution (1 mL). Subsequently, after an ultrasonic dispersion for 30 min, 4 μL of the catalyst slurry was dropped onto a glassy carbon electrode (GCE, 3 mm) and dried at room temperature to obtain the working electrode. A CHI 760E electrochemical workstation (Chenhua Co., Shanghai) was used for all the electrochemical tests performed using N2- or O2-saturated 0.1-M KOH solution, which was equipped with high-speed rotators procured from Pine Instruments. All tests were performed on a standard three-electrode system with the catalyst-coated GCE as the working electrode, Ag/AgCl as the reference electrode, and Pt wire as the counter electrode. Linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) was performed with the scanning speed of 10 mV/s. Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) was measured at an open circuit voltage with an alternating current amplitude of 5 mV over a frequency range of 0.01 Hz to 1 MHz. Cyclic voltammetry (CV) was conducted with a scanning speed of 50 mV/s. Stability tests were performed in O2-saturated 0.1 M KOH electrolyte by applying the cycling between − 0.3 V and + 0.1 V (vs Ag/AgCl) at a scanning speed of 50 mV/s for 1000 cycles and current versus time (I–t) chronoamperometrics for 20000 s. Methanol poisoning experiments were performed in O2-saturated 0.1-M KOH with 2-M methanol. For comparison, a commercial Pt/C (20 %) catalyst was tested under the same conditions. Rotating disk electrode (RDE) and rotating ring-disk electrode (RRDE) tests were conducted at varying rotating speeds from 625 to 1600 rpm with a scan rate of 10 mV/s for fitted the Koutecky–Levich (K–L) curves. The electron transfer numbers (n) can be obtained from the K–L equations as follows: (1) 1 j = 1 j K + 1 j L (2) j L = 0.62 nFA D 2 / 3 v − 1 / 6 ω 1 / 2 C O 2 where j, j K, and j L are the detected, kinetic, and diffusion-limiting current densities, respectively; n is the electron transfer number in the ORR; F is Faraday’s constant (F = 96485 C mol−1); A is the electrode area (A = 0.0707 cm2); D is the O2 diffusion coefficient (D = 1.9 × 10−5 cm2·s−1); v is the kinematic viscosity of the electrolyte (v = 1.13 × 10−2 cm2·s−1); ω is the rotating speed of the RDE; and C O2 is the concentration of O2 (C O2 = 1.2 × 10−3 mol·L−1). The RRDE tests were conducted at a rotating speed of 1600 rpm and a scan rate of 5 mV·s−1. The n and H2O2 yields can be calculated according to the following equations: (3) n = 4 j D j D + j R N (4) H 2 O 2 % = 2 j R N j D + j R N × 100 % Where j D and j R represent the faradic disk current density and the faradic ring current density, respectively, and N = 0.37 is the current collection efficiency. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Synthesis and morphology The synthetic routes are shown in Fig. 1, ZIF-8 powder was dispersed in a dichloroethane mixed TPPFe at a certain molar ratio of ZIF-8 to TPPFe (Table S1, Entry 2). Subsequently, hypercrosslinked TPPFe-coated ZIF-8 was pyrolyzed at different temperatures (600–900 ℃). Owing to oxygen containing group cooperated on the structure of ZIF-8, Fe3O4 was expected to be formed during the carbonization. Then, the Fe3O4-based ORR catalyst (FeTPP–ZIF-800) was obtained. The XRD data of the synthesized ZIF-8 in this study matched well with those reported [32] (Fig. S1). The FTIR results also indicated that the metalloporphyrin coated ZIF-8 (FeTPP-ZIF-8) was successfully synthesized (Fig. S2). The SEM images, atomic ratios, and surface area of the synthesized ZIF-8, FeTPP–ZIF, and FeTPP–ZIF-800 are shown in Fig. S3, Table S2, and Table S3, respectively. Fig.S3a-b clearly shows hypercrosslinked TPPFe coated on ZIF-8 structures. FeTPP–ZIF-800 was used as a model catalyst for TEM examination. As shown in Fig. 2a and S4, dark-shaded nanoparticles were located on the skeleton. High-resolution TEM images in Fig. 2b, c, and d revealed that these nanoparticles were nano-Fe3O4 because the measured lattice spacing was determined to be 0.253, 0.492, and 0.291 nm, corresponding to the (311), (111), and (220) planes of Fe3O4, respectively. The HAADF-STEM images (Fig. 2e) and the corresponding element mapping (Fig. 2f and Fig. S5) further confirmed the nanoparticles are composed of iron and oxygen. The TEM images under a small magnification were also provided (Fig. S5). C and N were evenly distributed throughout the ZIF-8 skeleton, which further characterized the structure of the C/N-coated nano-Fe3O4. The edge of the nanoparticle showed a characteristic spacing of 0.362 nm, corresponding to the (002) lattice plane of the graphitized carbon (JCPDS# 41–1487) [35] (Fig. 2c and d), suggested that the nano-Fe3O4 was coated with carbon layers. The special cladding structure around nano-Fe3O4 is most likely crucial for improving the electrical conductivity and protecting the Fe3O4 particles from electrolytic erosion. In addition, the Fe3O4 nanoparticles surrounded by the graphitized carbon show different crystal faces (Fig. 2d), which is favorable for the ORR activity and stability of the material [36]. In general, TEM characterization proved that Fe3O4 was expected to be formed was indeed synthesized and with a coated carbon layers which benefit to stability of catalyst. 3.2 Effect of carbonization temperature on the structure Different carbonization temperatures were used for regulating the structure of the catalyst. Four catalysts under carbonization temperatures of 600 ℃, 700 ℃, 800 ℃, and 900 ℃ were synthesized. All the prepared catalysts were examined by XRD ( Fig. 3a). Two broad peaks at approximately 25.7° and 42.9° corresponded to the (002) and (101) lattice planes of graphitized carbon (JCPDS NO. 41–1487) [37], respectively. These peaks were observed in all the samples. However, Fe3O4 was only formed at a temperature of 800 ℃. Amorphous iron was the main species at low temperatures (600 ℃ and 700 ℃). Zero-valent iron was detected at high temperatures (900 ℃). The characteristic peak at 44.6° belonging to the (110) lattice plane of zero-valent iron (JCPDS No. 06–0696) was observed in FeTPP–ZIF-900 [38]. Peaks at approximately 30.1°, 35.5°, and 62.6° belonging to the (220), (311), and (440) lattice planes of Fe3O4 (JCPDS No. 65–3107) [39] were only observed in FeTPP–ZIF-800, indicating that pyrolysis temperature is a key factor in controlling the production of the iron phase. These results demonstrated that the iron species could be regulated by the carbonization temperature, and Fe3O4 was formed in the target catalyst FeTPP–ZIF-800. N and O species were further examined by XPS because they are critical for ORR catalysis. Fig. S6 show an overall survey spectrum of the prepared catalyst with characteristic C 1s, N 1 s, O 1s, and Fe 2p peaks. The N 1s spectra can be deconvoluted into pyridinic-N (397.8 eV), metal-N (398.8 eV), pyrrole N (399.2 eV), graphitic–N (400.9 eV), and oxidized N (402.6 eV) (Fig. 3b) [29,40]. The Fe–N structure contributed dramatically to the catalysis of ORR [41], and a high content of Fe–N (37 %) was observed in the 800 ℃ sample. Nevertheless, this peak decreased at 600 ℃, 700 ℃, and 900 ℃ and it shifted to the pyridinic-N position with ZIF-800. Graphitic–N is generally believed to significantly contribute to ORR catalytic activity [42]. As shown in Fig. 3b, the graphitic–N peak increased with increasing temperature from 600 ℃ to 800 ℃, and then decreased at 900 ℃. In addition, compared with ZIF-800 and FeTPP-800, the graphitic–N in FeTPP–ZIF-800 increased from approximated 15–32 %, implying that introducing ZIF and FeTPP simultaneously increased the graphitic–N. These results revealed that temperature regulated the N-species, with 800 ℃ is probably the optimal choice. The O 1s spectra were deconvoluted into four peaks. The peaks at 529.9, 532.6, and 533.4 eV corresponding to adsorbed oxygen, carboxyl oxygen, and hydroxyls [2], respectively (Fig. 3c). Oxygen vacancy is a missing oxygen atom. Thus, when oxygen atom in metal oxides misses, it becomes easy to adsorb other oxygen-bearing species. So the O1 XPS signal at 531.2 eV is a circumstantial evidence for the presence of oxygen defect. Electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR) measurements were conducted to further identify the oxygen vacancies in FeTPP–ZIF-800 (Fig. S7). An EPR signal at a g-value of 2.004 was clearly observed, which further confirmed the existence of surface electron trapping sites caused by oxygen vacancy [43]. As shown in previous studies, vacancy oxygen is the most important O species in transition metal ORR catalysts. It can promote electrical conductivity, adjust surface electronic structure, and provide more active sites for electrocatalytic reaction [43]. Here, a high percentage of vacancy oxygen was observed in FeTPP–ZIF-800 (57 %) (Fig. 3c). The defect could promote electrical conductivity, adjust surface electronic structure and provide more active sites for ORR. The peak at 531.2 eV decreased gradually with temperature decreasing from 800 ℃ to 700 ℃ and 600 ℃, indicating a temperature-regulated oxygen vacancy formation. In addition, the peak of vacancy oxygen in FeTPP–ZIF-800 was higher than that of FeTPP-800, suggesting that introducing of ZIF benefited the formation of vacancy oxygen. In addition, the defects and graphitization degrees at different temperatures were evaluated by Raman spectroscopy (Fig. S8). The I D/I G increased with increasing pyrolysis temperature. Increasing I D/I G is expected to enhance overall electronic conductivity and therefore reduce the energy barrier for the ORR catalyst [44], which is beneficial for the ORR reaction. In addition, the I D/I G value of ZIF-800, FeTPP-800, and FeTPP–ZIF-800 is similar, suggesting that coating ZIF-8 on FeTPP did not decrease conductivity. 3.3 Effect of carbonization temperature on ORR catalytic activity To evaluate the ORR catalytic activity, CV was conducted in O2-saturated alkaline electrolytes ( Fig. 4a). As can be seen in Fig. 4a, all the Fe-based electrodes displayed a well-defined cathodic ORR peak at potentials between − 0.2 and − 0.05 V (vs. Ag/AgCl electrode). The FeTPP–ZIF-800 electrode showed the highest catalytic activity, having the most positive ORR peak potential and the strongest cathodic current. Moreover, the LSV curves recorded on a RDE in the same solution showed that the FeTPP–ZIF-800 electrode exhibited the best ORR performance (Fig. 4b); it exhibited the most positive halfwave potential (−0.132 V) and the highest limiting current density (5.1 mA·cm−2), which is even better than that of the commercial Pt/C catalyst (−0.114 and 4.8 mA·cm−2 as the halfwave potential and limiting current density, respectively) (Fig. 4b and Fig. S9). In general, by comparing ORR catalytic activity between different carbonization temperatures, 800 ℃ is proved to be the best temperature for this catalyst. 3.4 The catalytic mechanism of the high-activity catalyst FeTPP–ZIF-800 FeTPP–ZIF-800 showed the best ORR catalytic performance in this study. The introducing of FeTPP and ZIF both increased N contents. In particular, pyridinic-N could promote the onset potential and graphitic-n could enhance the structural stability and ORR limiting current density [45,46]. These structures may contribute a lot for the high catalytic efficiency. Thus, the catalytic mechanism of FeTPP–ZIF-800 was further studied in detail. The ORR reaction can be described as one-step 4e− reduction process and multi-step 2e− reduction process. Theoretical studies show that the 4e− transition of O2 could increase the output voltage of the catalyst, and improve the efficiency of the fuel cell [47]. To deeper investigate the electrochemical kinetics of catalyst, the number of transferred electrons n was plotted using different rotating speeds of 625–2500 rpm ( Fig. 5a). All the K–L plots derived from Fig. 5a were linear under all potentials, indicating first-order reaction kinetics with respect to O2 concentration (Fig. 5b). The calculated n is 3.98 according to the K–L equation, which is very close to the ideal value of 4. And the n from the RRDE tests was 3.88, which is close to that of Pt/C (3.98) (Fig. 5c). As H2O2 is the main intermediate in the ORR processes, the yield of H2O2 production was calculated. The H2O2 yield of FeTPP–ZIF-800 was below 5 % in the test potential range (Fig. 5c), further supporting that ORR catalyzed on FeTPP–ZIF-800 follows the high efficient 4 e− pathway ideally. We further investigate the effect of material conductivity on the electron transfers rate by EIS tests (Fig. 5d). The arc diameter associated with FeTPP–ZIF-800 was 90.2 Ω, which was close to commercial Pt/C (84.3 Ω) and better than ZIF-800 (100.3 Ω), indicating that the catalyst had good conductivity, resulting in a faster electron transport during ORR. This is probably because, the oxygen defects, which have been confirmed by EPR and XPS, promoted the electron transfer efficiency and made up for the poor conductivity of oxide [48]. The stability and tolerance of the catalyst were further studied (Fig. 5e-h). The long-term stability was evaluated by chronoamperometry in an O2-saturated 0.1-M KOH solution at a fixed potential of 0.65 V. Consequently, after an i–t test of 20000 s, the current density of commercial Pt/C decreased by 21 % of its initial value, whereas a small degradation of FeTPP–ZIF-800 (7 %) was observed (Fig. 5e). Fig. 5f shows the results of methanol crossover tests; after the addition of methanol (2 mol·L−1), the current of the commercial Pt/C catalyst considerably dropped to less than 65 % of its original value and that of the FeTPP–ZIF-800 recovered rapidly with almost no loss, suggesting the high-methanol tolerance of FeTPP–ZIF-800. Furthermore, CVs of FeTPP–ZIF-800 and commercial Pt/C before and after an ADT were obtained (Fig. 5g). The cyclic condition of the ADT usually causes the corrosion of carbon supports, which accelerates the agglomeration and Ostwald ripening of metal nanoparticles[49,50]. No obvious change was observed in FeTPP–ZIF-800 after ADTs (Fig. 5g and h); nevertheless, the limited current for Pt/C decreased by approximately 15 % (Fig. 5h). These results indicated that the nano-Fe3O4-doped Fe–N–C ORR catalyst (i.e., FeTPP–ZIF-800) in this study possessed excellent catalytic stability, which is better than that of the commercial Pt/C. TEM images (Fig. 2c-d) shows nano-Fe3O4 was coated by carbon layers. This structure could both isolate the active center from the electrolyte and improve the conductivity. Thus, the coated structure reduces the corrosion of the electrolyte to nano-Fe3O4 and prevents the loss of active species, which improved the stability of the catalyst. Although Fe based material is usually not resistant to acid corrosion thus Pt/C tends to perform better in acidic conditions [51], the aforementioned results suggest that the nonprecious FeTPP–ZIF-800 in this study has comparable onset potential, higher current density, excellent tolerance to methanol and superior durability in the ORR, which shows an excellent catalytic performance toward ORR in alkaline media. As shown in Fig. 4, carbonization temperature is a critical factor impacting the catalyst. Thus, the mechanism of carbonization temperature impacting catalytic activity was further studied. Compared with FeTPP–ZIF-600, FeTPP–ZIF-700, and FeTPP–ZIF-900, the structure of FeTPP–ZIF-800 had two critical differences as shown in the following section. Temperature regulated the iron species (Fig. 3a). Fe3O4 was formed in FeTPP–ZIF-800, the dominant iron species in FeTPP–ZIF-600 and FeTPP–ZIF-700 was amorphous iron and that in FeTPP–ZIF-900 was Fe0. According to thermodynamic theory, this is most likely because Fe3O4 is more stable than amorphous iron at high temperatures. As nitrate ions could decomposed at high temperature and release oxygen, the oxygen atoms in Fe3O4 were probably from the nitrate ions that cooperated on ZIF-8 [52]. However, iron oxide can be reduced to Fe0 by C in the skeleton at 900 ℃ [2,39]. Fe3O4 can promote the adsorption of O species on surfaces, which may increase the reactant concentration for ORR and promote the overall activity [40]. To confirm the critical role of Fe3O4 in the obtained catalyst, TPP–ZIF-800 without iron was synthesized, which showed extremely low ORR activity (Fig. S10 a-b). Meanwhile, FeTPP–ZIF-800 was treated with hydrochloric acid to remove the Fe3O4 nanoparticles for comparison (Fig. S11 a-b). The ORR catalytic activity results showed a 30 mV negative shift of the halfwave potential and a 20 % decrease in the diffusion-limited current in FeTPP–ZIF-800–HCl compared to FeTPP–ZIF-800 (Fig. S11 c-d). Moreover, catalysts with different iron ratios were synthesized at a constant temperature of 800 ℃ (Table S1 and Fig. S12). The Fe3O4 XRD peak decreased upon decreasing of the FeTPP ratio from ZIF-8:FeTPP = 1:0.64–1:0.31 (Fig. S12a), and the catalytic diffusion-limited current was decreased from 3.4 to 5.1 mA·cm−2 with decreasing Fe3O4 (Fig. S12f). These results all confirmed that the nano-Fe3O4 formed at 800 ℃ was essential for a high catalytic efficiency. The temperature regulated the ratio of oxygen and nitrogen species (Fig. 3b and c and Fig. 6). As shown in Fig. 6, the content of oxygen vacancy, Fe–N, and graphite–N increased with increasing temperature from 600 ℃ to 800 ℃ and then decreased at 900 ℃. Reductive species such as C and H can reduce metal oxides to form oxygen vacancies; during this process, carbonization temperature significantly impacts the oxygen vacancy content [2,39]. As the microporous organic polymers were rich in C and H, oxygen overflowed from the metal oxide at high pyrolysis temperatures. Transition metal–nitrogen coordination sites (M–Nx, M = Fe) are generally considered to be the most promising substitutes for ORR [53]. In this study, the content of Fe–N reached a maximum at 800 ℃ (Fig. 6). The graphitic–N atoms in the carbon lattice facilitate electron transfer from the carbon electronic bands to the antibonding orbitals of O2 [54]. Hence, increasing graphitic–N is crucial for enhancing ORR activity [55]. The graphitic–N reached a maximum of 33 % at 800 ℃ (Fig. 6). Therefore, changing the temperature not only regulated the iron species but also controlled the content of oxygen vacancies, Fe–N, and graphite–N, thus regulating the ORR activity. 4 Conclusion In this study, a ZIF ORR electrocatalyst with nano-Fe3O4 and oxygen vacancies, which was derived from a hypercrosslinked iron porphyrin coated ZIF-8, was synthesized. The obtained catalyst (FeTPP–ZIF-800) was abundant in Fe–N and graphitic–N structure. The catalyst was found to possess a superior ORR catalytic performance compared to commercial Pt/C with a high halfwave potential (−0.132 V), strong limiting current density (5.1 mA·cm−2), excellent stability (93 % activity retention after 20000 s), excellent methanol resistance, and high reaction selectivity (4 e− catalytic process). The in situ formed nano-Fe3O4 doped on the skeleton was suggested to be the critical active species promoting catalytic efficiency. Pyrolyzation temperature was clarified to be crucial for the ORR activity. A temperature of 800 ℃ was optimal because the Fe3O4 crystal can only be formed at high temperatures (800 ℃). The content of O vacancies, Fe–N, and graphite–N reached a maximum at 800 ℃. This study clarified that the in situ introduction of nano-Fe3O4 into a hyper-crosslinked ZIF skeleton is a feasible strategy for improving ORR capabilities, which could be beneficial for fundamentally understanding the design of high-performance ORR catalysts. coredata.dc:description: In this study, a novel and highly efficient ORR catalyst is designed via the pyrolysis of zeolitic imidazole framework-8 (ZIF-8) under the protection of hypercrosslinked iron porphyrins. Fe3O4 nanoparticles with oxygen vacancies are formed in situ and promoting catalytic efficiency. Benefiting from the synergistic effect among the Fe3O4 and ZIF-8 skeleton, the hybrid catalyst exhibits excellent ORR activity even surpassing commercial Pt/C. The pyrolyzation temperature is studied in detail and determined to be a crucial parameter for ORR performance. Nano-Fe3O4, which has high catalytic efficiency, is formed in situ at 800 ℃. Amorphous iron is formed at 600 ℃ and 700 ℃, and zero-valent iron is formed at 900 ℃. The content of oxygen vacancies, Fe–N, and graphite–N, which are beneficial to the ORR reaction, are all reached to a maximum at 800 ℃. This study provides a new approach to design highly active Fe3O4-based electrocatalytic materials.
coredata.dc:title: Coupling nano-Fe3O4 with oxygen vacancies on a hypercrosslinked iron porphyrin-coated ZIF-8 as a high-efficiency oxygen reduction reaction electrocatalyst
